<p>The Sum Rule also applies to subtraction. In this case, the function that is to be differentiated has four terms. Thus, the functionâ€™s derivative can be obtained by differentiating each term separately.</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	\ddx{(y)} &amp;= \ddx\br{ x^3+7x^{-6}-2x^5+\frac{\pi}{3} } \\
	\dydx &amp;= \ddx(x^3)+\ddx(7x^{-6})-\ddx(2x^5)+\ddx\br{ \frac{\pi}{3} } \\%\quad \text{\tcA{$\pi$ is a constant}}\\
	&amp;= 3x^{3-1}+(-6)7x^{-6-1}-(5)2x^{5-1}+0 \\
	&amp;= 3x^2-42x^{-7}-10x^4 \\
	&amp;= 3x^2-\frac{42}{x^7}-10x^4		\tagans
\end{align*}\]

